```javascript
function isPrime(n) {
  // edge cases
  if (n <= 1) return false;
  if (n === 2) return true;

  // check divisibility by 2 and odd numbers up to sqrt(n)
  for (let I = 3; I * i <= n; I += 2) {
    if (n % I === 0) return false;
  }

  return true;
}

// example usage
const numbers = [7, 18, 14, 9, 16];
for (let num of numbers) {
  if (isPrime(num)) {
    console.log(`${num} is a prime number`);
  }
}
```

This code defines a `isPrime()` helper function that determines whether a given integer `n` is a prime number or not. It first handles some common edge cases such as `n=1`, which is never prime, and `n=2`, which is always prime. Then it loops through odd integers from 3 up to the square root of `n`. If any of these integers divide evenly into `n`, then we know immediately that `n` cannot be a prime number. Finally, if none of the tested values divided `n`, then it must be prime!

In the main part of our program, we simply iterate over each number in the array using a `for...of` loop, calling `isPrime()` on each value and printing out its result to the console if it's a prime. This will output something like:

